ğŸ“Œ 2. Prefix Sum
A prefix sum is a powerful technique to preprocess an array for fast range sum queries.

ğŸ¯ Use Case:
Given arr = [2, 4, 6, 1, 3], find sum from index 1 to 3.
Instead of summing 4 + 6 + 1 every time, use:
prefix[i] = prefix[i-1] + arr[i];
Then, sum(1,3) = prefix[3] - prefix[0]

âœ… Prefix Sum Steps:
Create a prefix array: prefix[0] = arr[0]

For i from 1 to n-1:
prefix[i] = prefix[i-1] + arr[i]

To get sum from index l to r:
sum = prefix[r] - prefix[l - 1]

âš¡ Efficiency:
Preprocessing: O(n)
Range query: O(1)
This is a big improvement from O(n) per query.


Understanding Big O notation like O(n) is crucial for learning Data Structures and Algorithms (DSA). 
Itâ€™s how we measure the efficiency of a program â€” especially how well it performs as the input size increases.

Let me break it down in simple terms:

ğŸš€ What is Big O Notation?
Big O notation describes the time or space complexity of an algorithm â€” in other words:

How fast (or slow) does your code run as the input gets bigger?

ğŸ“¦ Real-Life Analogy
Imagine you're reading names from a list of 1,000 people to find one person.
Linear Search (O(n)): You go one-by-one until you find it. Worst case? You read all 1,000 names.
Binary Search (O(log n)): You cut the list in half each time. Much faster!

ğŸ§  Common Time Complexities (from fast to slow):
Big O            	Meaning                            	    Example
O(1)	          Constant time â€“ same always	              Accessing arr[5]
O(log n)	      Logarithmic â€“ cuts in half each time	    Binary Search
O(n)	          Linear â€“ grows with input	                Looping once through array
O(n log n)    	Linearithmic â€“ sorting	                  Merge Sort, Quick Sort
O(nÂ²)	          Quadratic â€“ nested loops                	Comparing all pairs in array
O(2^n)	        Exponential â€“ terrible for large n	      Recursive brute-force algorithms

ğŸ§® Prefix Sum Efficiency Example
Letâ€™s say you are asked:

"Given this array, find the sum from index l to r, many times."
âŒ Without Prefix Sum (Brute Force):

Each time:
int sum = 0;
for (int i = l; i <= r; i++) {
    sum += arr[i];
}

ğŸ•’ Time Complexity: O(n) â€” you loop every time!

âœ… With Prefix Sum:
You do this once:

prefix[0] = arr[0];
for (int i = 1; i < arr.Length; i++) {
    prefix[i] = prefix[i - 1] + arr[i];
}

Then for any range l to r:

int sum = prefix[r] - (l > 0 ? prefix[l - 1] : 0);
ğŸ•’ Now, each query is done in O(1) time!
Even 1 million queries will be super fast âš¡

ğŸ“˜ How to Learn Big O Step-by-Step
Start with simple loops
for, while â€” count how many times it runs.
Practice common patterns
Nested loops â†’ O(nÂ²)
Divide and Conquer â†’ O(log n) or O(n log n)
Use visualization
Websites like Visualgo and Big O Cheat Sheet help a lot.

Ask yourself during coding:
â€œIf the array has 1 million items, will my solution work fast?â€

âš™ï¸ Common Mistakes to Avoid
Forgetting 0-based indexing.
Using prefix sum incorrectly at boundaries (l = 0).
Off-by-one errors.

âœ… How to Analyze Array Problems
Question to Ask	Example
What's the size of the input?	Small = brute force OK; Large = optimize
Are there repeated queries?	Use prefix sum or precomputation
Is order important?	Sorting or reverse traversal?
Are there nested iterations?	Try to reduce time from O(nÂ²) to O(n)



